          "title": "The theophanic vision — the Warrior from Edom (63:1-6)",
          "body": "Isaiah 63 opens with one of the most dramatic theophanies in the Old Testament: a solitary figure marching from Edom, His garments stained crimson, questioned by a watchman and identifying Himself as 'mighty to save' (63:1). The winepress monologue that follows (63:3-6) is an act of self-declaration by the divine Warrior — He trod the peoples alone, looked for a human helper and found none, and so His own arm accomplished the victory. The imagery is unsparing: blood sprinkled on garments, peoples made drunk in wrath, lifeblood poured on the earth. The justice administered is total and solitary. Christian interpreters from Justin Martyr through John Calvin and into contemporary scholarship have seen in this Warrior the messianic figure identified more fully in Revelation 19:11-16, where 'His robe was dipped in blood' (Rev. 19:13) and He treads 'the wine press of the fierce wrath of God' (Rev. 19:15). The theological anchor of the vision is verse 4: the day of vengeance and the year of redemption are not in tension — they are the same act, seen from two perspectives simultaneously."
